død","1480–1508":"1480–1508","1500–1584":"1500–1584","1507–1568":"1507–1568","1508–1542":"1508–1542","1485–Female":"1485–Afdød","1568":"1568","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","abt 1505":"omkring 1505","1485":"1485","1584":"1584","1508":"1508","1507":"1507","1480":"1480","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","England":"England, United Kingdom","St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"nl":{"1485–":"1485–Overleden","1480–1508":"1480–1508","1500–1584":"1500–1584","1507–1568":"1507–1568","1508–1542":"1508–1542","1485–Female":"1485–Overleden","1568":"1568","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","abt 1505":"circa 1505","1485":"1485","1584":"1584","1508":"1508","1507":"1507","1480":"1480","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"en":{"1485–":"1485–Deceased","1480–1508":"1480–1508","1500–1584":"1500–1584","1507–1568":"1507–1568","1508–1542":"1508–1542","1485–Female":"1485–Deceased","1568":"1568","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","abt 1505":"about 1505","1485":"1485","1584":"1584","1508":"1508","1507":"1507","1480":"1480","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","England":"England, United Kingdom","St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Constantine","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Constantin</i>, <i>Costantin</i> (from Latin <i>Constantinus</i>, a derivative of <i>constans</i> ‘steadfast’). The name was popular in Continental Europe, and to a lesser extent in England, as having been borne by the first Christian ruler of the Roman Empire, Constantine the Great (<i>c.</i> 280–337), in whose honor Byzantium was renamed Constantinople. In some cases the name may be an Americanized form of one of the many cognates in other languages, in particular Greek <b>Konstantinos</b>.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Cotentin (Coutances) in La Manche, France (see   Constance   2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Constance","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): from the medieval French female personal name <i>Constance</i>, Latin <i>Constantia</i>, originally a feminine form of <i>Constantius</i> (see   Constant  ), but later taken as the abstract noun <i>constantia</i> ‘steadfastness’. Occasionally also from the masculine form <i>Constantin</i>.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Coutances in La Manche (France)."]},{"name":"Costin","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Costin</i>, <i>Costein</i>, a shortened form of Old French   Constantine  , Anglo-Norman French <i>Costetin</i>, from Latin <i>Constantinus</i>.","English, Scottish, and Manx: in northwestern England it may be a variant of Manx   Costain  ."]},{"name":"Constant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Jacques, Anatole, Andre, Berard, Fernand, Gardy, Gesner, Jean Claude, Nazaire, Normand, Pierre, Thierry.","French and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the French personal name <i>Constant</i>, which can be from Latin <i>Constans</i>, genitive <i>Constantis</i>, meaning ‘steadfast, faithful’ (from <i>constans</i>, present participle of the verb <i>constare</i> ‘stand fast, be consistent’), and also from Latin <i>Constantius</i>, a derivative of <i>Constans</i>, borne by a 2nd-century Christian martyr, bishop of Perugia. Compare   Constantine  .","American shortened form of French   Constantineau  ."]},{"name":"Constantin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Raoul, Andre, Antoine, Armand, Calice, Eusebe, Fernand, Michel, Micheline, Pierre, Ravis.  Romanian Constantin, Mihaela, Petre, Cornel, Dragos, Dumitru, Estera, Floarea, Nicoleta, Sorin, Stelian, Vasile.  Spanish Cristina, Ana, Carlos, Elena, Jesus, Liliana, Lourdes, Luis.","Romanian and French; Spanish (<b>Constantín</b>): from local equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Constantinus</i> or Greek <i>Konstantinos</i> (see   Constantine  ).","Galician (<b>Constantín</b>): habitational name from any of the places called Constantín in Lugo province, Galicia (Spain)."]},{"name":"Konstantinidis","meanings":["Greek: patronymic from the personal name <i>Konstantinos</i>, from Latin <i>Constantinus</i> (see   Constantine  ). The suffix <i>-idis</i>, meaning ‘son/descendant of’, is a variant of the classical <i>-ides</i> which was revived in the 19th century, in particular by Greeks from Asia Minor and Eastern Thrace. Compare   Constantin   3 and   Constantinides  ."]},{"name":"Considine","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, John Patrick.","Irish (Clare): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Consaidín</b> ‘son of <i>Consaidín</i>’, Gaelic form of   Constantine  . This name is borne by a branch of the O'Briens in County Clare."]},{"name":"Constantino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Jorge, Juan, Carlos, Alicia, Angelina, Cesar, Conrado, Demetrio, Florentina, Manuel.  Italian Antonio, Angelo, Salvatore, Carlo, Domenic, Filomena, Geno, Ignazio, Maddalena, Nunzi, Raimondo, Rocco.","Spanish, Portuguese, and Italian: from the personal name <i>Constantino</i>, from Latin <i>Constantinus</i> (see   Constantine  )."]},{"name":"Costantino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Antonio, Aldo, Angelo, Gino, Rocco, Carmela, Carmine, Sal, Saverio, Silvio, Umberto.","Italian (southern): from the personal name <i>Costantino</i> (see   Constantine  )."]},{"name":"Koistinen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Finnish Pentti, Pertti, Rauni, Seppo.  Scandinavian Erik.","Finnish: from the personal name <i>Koisti</i>, Karelian form of <i>Konstantin</i> (see   Constantine  ), + the surname suffix <i>-nen</i>. This surname is found mainly in eastern Finland, in the Savo region."]},{"name":"Constantinou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Greek Costas, Andreas, Constantinos, Kyriacos, Marios, Angelos, Charalambos, Constantine, Despina, Kyriakos, Panayiotis, Panos.","Greek (typically Cypriot): patronymic from the genitive case of the personal name <i>Constantinos</i>, a typically Cypriot variant of <i>Konstantinos</i>, from Latin <i>Constantinus</i> (see   Constantine  )."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Constantine was born in 1485, in Wales. She married John Young about 1505, in Pembrokeshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1485–":"1485–Surnud","1480–1508":"1480–1508","1500–1584":"1500–1584","1507–1568":"1507–1568","1508–1542":"1508–1542","1485–Female":"1485–Surnud","1568":"1568","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","abt 1505":"umbes 1505","1485":"1485","1584":"1584","1508":"1508","1507":"1507","1480":"1480","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1485–":"1485–Kuollut","1480–1508":"1480–1508","1500–1584":"1500–1584","1507–1568":"1507–1568","1508–1542":"1508–1542","1485–Female":"1485–Kuollut","1568":"1568","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","abt 1505":"noin 1505","1485":"1485","1584":"1584","1508":"1508","1507":"1507","1480":"1480","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1485–":"1485–Décédée","1480–1508":"1480–1508","1500–1584":"1500–1584","1507–1568":"1507–1568","1508–1542":"1508–1542","1485–Female":"1485–Décédée","1568":"1568","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","abt 1505":"environ 1505","1485":"1485","1584":"1584","1508":"1508","1507":"1507","1480":"1480","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Galles","Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Hodgeston, Pembrokeshire, Galles","Wales":"Galles","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"St Davids, Pembrokeshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Eleanor Constantine est née en 1485, à Galles. Elle a épousé John Young environ 1505, à Pembrokeshire, Galles. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils e